<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-561-274  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 561 274.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  August 21 1989 n552 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Waveform versatility: digital function generators overtakinganalog. (Technology Update feature)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Costlow, Terry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Function generators using flexible digital technology are makingsignificant inroads into the testing and instrumentation market.andO;Arbitrary function generators offer the advantage of being able tobuild any waveform required by an engineering agenda.andP;  Observerscompare them to the digital oscilloscope, expecting them to followthe same pattern of beginning with specific applications and beingemployed for increasingly generalized ones.andP;  Companies such asLeCroy Corp, Analogics Corp and Hewlett-Packard are stepping uptheir product development plans for the technology.andP;  In 1988,arbitrary function generators accounted for 25 percent of the $91million worldwide market in function generators.andP;  By 1992arbitrary instruments are expected to account for more than halfof an expanded $160 million market.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Ticker:    HWP.andO;Topic:     WaveformsMarket ShareDigital CommunicationsAnalog CommunicationsSignal ProcessingProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Worldwide sales of arbitrary function generators, (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>